05220nam a22007455i 9789048543885DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485438857 a10.1515/97890485438852doi  a(DE-B1597)612953  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 4aPN1993.5.B28 7aART0570002bisacsh04a791.43094962231 aGrgic, Ana, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEarly Cinema, Modernity and Visual Culture :bThe Imaginary of the Balkans /cAna Grgic. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (278 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEastern European screen cultures ;v300tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tAcknowledgements -- tForeword: Travelling Down /Travelling Through -- tPreface: The Balkan Imaginary of Ruins -- tIntroduction: Charting the Terrain: Early Cinema in the Balkans -- t1. Visual Culture in the Balkans, Haptic Visuality, and Archival Moving Images -- t2. Historicizing the Balkan Spectator and the Embodied Cinema Experience -- t3. Mapping Constellations : Movement and Cross-cultural Exchange of Images, Practices, and People -- t4. Imagining the Balkans: The Cinematic Gaze from the Outside -- t5. ‘Made in the Balkans’: Mirroring the Self -- tConclusion: The Future Perfect of Early Balkan Cinema -- tBibliography -- tAppendix -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe end of the nineteenth century saw the Balkans animated with cultural movements and socio-political turmoil. Alongside these developments, the proliferation of print media and the arrival of moving images was transforming urban life and played a significant role in the creation of national culture. Based on archival research and previously overlooked footage and early press materials, Imaginary of the Balkans: Visual Culture, Modernity and Early Cinema is the first study on early cinema in the region from a transnational and cross-cultural perspective. This work investigates how the unique geopolitical positioning of the Balkan space and the multi-cultural identity of its communities influenced and shaped visual culture and early cinema development. Moreover, it examines the relationship between the new medium and visual culture through the notion of the haptic, and explores the role early cinema and foreign productions played in the construction of Balkanist and semi-colonial discourses. Reframing hierarchical relations between ‘centres’ and ‘peripheries’, this book departs from approaches such as “new cinema history” and “vernacular modernity” to counter modernity discourses of “lacks and absences”, and instead, establishes new connections between moving image and print artefacts, early film practitioners and intellectuals, the socio-cultural context and cultural responses to the new visual medium.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aMotion pictureszBalkan PeninsulaxHistory. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aHeritage Studies. 4aMedia Studies. 7aART / Film & Video.2bisacsh  aBalkan Studies, Early Cinema, Archives, Cultural Memory, Film Phenomenology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311074322708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAmsterdam University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076709408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2021 Part 2z978311074335708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2022 Part 2z978311076700140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9789048543885zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789048543885423Coveruhttps://www.deg